In OOP, a class is a blueprint or template that defines the properties and behavior of an object. It is a abstract concept that represents a category of objects that share common characteristics. A class defines the structure and behavior of an object, including its attributes (data) and methods (functions).

An object, on the other hand, is an instance of a class. It is a concrete representation of a class, with its own set of attributes and methods. An object has its own state and behavior, and it can be manipulated and interacted with independently of other objects.

In other words, a class is a design pattern or template, while an object is a specific implementation of that pattern.

