```java
public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        // If n is less than 1, it cannot be a power of 3
        if (n < 1) {
            return false;
        }

        // While n is divisible by 3, keep dividing it by 3
        while (n % 3 == 0) {
            n /= 3;
        }

        // If n is 1, then it is a power of 3, otherwise it is not
        return n == 1;
    }
}
```
### Explanation

This solution uses a while loop to continuously divide the input number `n` by 3 as long as it is divisible by 3. This is because any power of 3 will have a factor of 3 in its prime factorization, and by continuously dividing by 3, we are essentially removing these factors. 

If `n` is 1 after this process, it means that it was originally a power of 3 (since 3^x = 1 only when x = 0, and we excluded the case where n = 0 in the first if statement). If `n` is not 1, it means that it was not a power of 3.

This solution has a time complexity of O(log n) because the while loop will terminate when `n` is no longer divisible by 3, which happens after at most log(n) iterations (since each iteration divides `n` by 3).

